Kansas State coach Deb Patterson nearly
ran out of adjectives to describe forward Kendra Wecker.
article.headline: Wecker scores 26 points, grabs 14 rebounds for K-State
article.linkText: With Wecker leading the way, No. 3 K-State takes Preseason WNIT
article.story:
MANHATTAN, Kan. (AP) -- Kansas State coach Deb Patterson nearly
ran out of adjectives to describe forward Kendra Wecker.

	   Wecker had a career-high 26 points and 14 rebounds, and Laurie
Koehn scored 23 as Kansas State (No. 3 ESPN/USA Today; No. 4 Associated Press) beat No. 14 Penn State 88-66
to win the Preseason WNIT on Sunday.

	   ''Kendra was absolutely tremendous, phenomenal, extraordinary,
dominant,'' Patterson said. ''She was an absolute champion. She put
Penn State on their heels and was virtually unstoppable.''

	   Kansas State (4-0), which beat opponents by an average of 16
points during the weeklong tournament, pulled away from Penn State (4-1) with an 8-0 run with 4:34 remaining to win its first
WNIT title.

	   Koehn started the second half with five consecutive points to make
an eight-point halftime lead grow to 13 points. The Lady Lions trimmed it to nine
before Wecker, the tournament most valuable player, answered with two
consecutive baskets and Penn State never got closer.

	   Wecker averaged 22 points and 11 rebounds during the four-game
tournament. She had a double-double in all but one game.

	   ''I'd take her in a fox hole with me,'' Penn State coach Rene
Portland said. ''There's Koehn who shoots with finesse and their
inside player who shoots with finesse. And then she just does it
all. She's a bull in a china shop. I mean that in the most positive
way.''

	   Nicole Ohlde had 17 points and 10 rebounds, and Megan Mahoney
scored 16 for Kansas State.

	   Kelly Mazzante, who came in averaging 29.8 points a game, had
18. Tanisha Wright led Penn State with 26 points and Ashli
Schwab had 13.

	   ''We knew coming in that she was a tremendous player,'' Mahoney
said of Mazzante. ''You can't stop her because she's just such a
good player. But we just tried to contain her.''

	   The Wildcats held Mazzante, the nation's leading scorer last
season, to five first-half points, but Wright made up for it with
19 in the first 20 minutes.

	   ''They had two people coming at me every time,'' Mazzante said.

	   Then Koehn scored 10 consecutive points to give the Wildcats a
32-22 lead. Penn State closed to four points before Koehn stole the
ball from Jess Strom near halfcourt and finished it with a layup,
bringing Bramlage Coliseum to a roar.

	   ''We answered the challenge of containing a very potent
offensive team,'' Patterson said.

	   Portland is still one victory shy of becoming the seventh coach in
women's college basketball to win 600 games. Portland is 599-207 in
27 years of coaching.
